Characterisation of health and social development.

Almeida RM(1), Thamer M, Attinger EO.

Author information:
(1)University of Virginia, Health Sciences Center, Charlottesville.

The relative performance of less developed countries in their health, 
demographic and economic sectors was assessed by means of comparative indices 
constructed with the help of a factor analysis. This approach reduces the 
problems usually associated with such indices, like the arbitrary weighting of 
their components.

PIP: A new method of comparing the performance of developing countries, similar 
to the physical quality of life index, was developed using factor analysis of 
the social, demographic, economic and health variables weighted by their 
loadings of the factor they represented. Data were taken from the World Health 
Organization, the World Bank, and the United Nations Research Institute for 
Social Development for 67 countries. For each year countries were classified as 
developed, transitional and less developed, using an infant mortality of 50/1000 
and combined life expectancy of 65 years as the cut-off. First the factors 
explaining most of the variance were selected in each category, then countries 
were ranked. The most important factors were for health: life expectancy, crude 
death rate, infant mortality; for social: literacy; for demography: population 
growth rate, percentage of non-working age population, and crude birth rate; for 
economics: gross domestic product, energy consumption, and rate of urbanization. 
Countries that moved from less developed to developed were not necessarily 
first-ranked in economic factors, e.g., China and Sri Lanka improved in health 
indices, while Costa Rica improved in demographic indices. This method provides 
a way to compare common and distinctive features of countries without using 
arbitrary criteria.

