870. J Biosoc Sci. 1992 Jan;24(1):17-24. doi: 10.1017/s0021932000006763.

Measurement of post-partum amenorrhoea in Bangladesh.

Rahman MM(1).

Author information:
(1)Department of Statistics, University of Chittagong, Bangladesh.

Reported information on the duration of post-partum amenorrhoea usually shows 
considerable number preference, particularly at 6-monthly intervals. This paper 
presents a technique for smoothing such amenorrhoea data using a modified 
exponential curve. An attempt has also been made to estimate the average number 
of months a mother is expected to remain amenorrhoeic.

PIP: A researcher used data on about 4,000 women from the 1975 Bangladesh 
Fertility Survey (part of the World Fertility Survey) to illustrate a technique 
to smooth amenorrhea data since the mothers preferred to report 6 month 
intervals and ton construct an amenorrhea life table for mothers from 
Bangladesh. Specifically he categorized women by marriage cohort and used 7, 13, 
19, 25, 31, 37, 43, and 49 month durations for the life table and to modify an 
exponential curve to smooth the amenorrhea data. He further broke down the 
durations to 1 month when he compared women married between 1945-1949 and 
1960-1964 for 2 amenorrhea life tables. When he plotted the observed and 
estimated values, he learned that a shift in the percentage of women 
experiencing postpartum amenorrhea for lower durations (up to 7 months) occurred 
over time. Further the estimates of the amenorrhea life tables confirmed that 
the duration of postpartum amenorrhea has fallen. In addition, these tables 
showed that 50% of the women began menstruating again around month 9 postpartum 
and that, by month 33 postpartum, 90% did. In conclusion, the modified 
exponential curves appeared to be sound for smoothing postpartum amenorrhea data 
in Bangladesh.

