871. J Biosoc Sci. 1992 Jan;24(1):89-95. doi: 10.1017/s0021932000006829.

Correlation between subsequent lengths of postpartum amenorrhoea in a 
prospective study of breast-feeding women in rural Bangladesh.

Ford K(1).

Author information:
(1)Department of Population Planning and International Health, School of Public 
Health, University of Michigan, Ann Arbor.

The relationship between subsequent lengths of lactational amenorrhoea for 
individual women in a prospective study of breast-feeding women in Bangladesh 
was studied. The data indicate that previous length of amenorrhoea has 
significant predictive value for the subsequent length of amenorrhoea. 
Information on previous experience with lactational amenorrhoea should be 
therefore incorporated into guidelines for the introduction of family planning 
during lactation.

PIP: A researcher drew from 1975-1979 prospective data on about 2500 women from 
14 villages in rural Matlab, Bangladesh to determine the relationship between 
subsequent durations of lactational amenorrhea in breast feeding women. The life 
table analysis included 1852 postpartum amenorrhea intervals. The median 
interval was 14.66 months for all births and 15.5 months when infant deaths were 
excluded. The median duration of postpartum amenorrhea for all women who 
remained amenorrheic after a live birth was 15.68 months and for 2nd and later 
births it was 13.74 months. The shorter the prior interval, the greater was the 
risk of quick resumption of menstruation. In fact, the relative risk (RR) was 9 
for women with an earlier interval of 6 months (p.01), 5 for those with a 6-12 
month interval (p.01), and 2.5 for those with a 13-18 month interval (p.05). 
Years of schooling had a significant effect on resumption of menstruation 
(p.01), but the researcher could not determine if it was due to other aspects of 
differences in patterns of breast feeding by socioeconomic status. She did not 
directly measure frequency and duration of each feeding. The introduction of 
solid food supplementation did not affect resumption of menstruation at all. In 
conclusion, the researcher recommended that since previous length of postpartum 
amenorrhea had a considerable predictive effect on subsequent lengths of 
postpartum amenorrhea, family planning workers should include previous 
experience with postpartum amenorrhea to algorithms for the introduction of 
